# CSS Pseudo Classes

Pseudo classes define the special state of an element.

They allow developers to style elements based on user interaction or element state.

## Common Pseudo Classes

### :hover

Applies styles when a user places the mouse over an element.

```css
button:hover {
    background-color: blue;
    color: white;
}
```

### :focus

Applies styles when an input field receives focus.

```css
input:focus {
    border: 2px solid blue;
    outline: none;
}
```

### :active

Applies styles while an element is being clicked.

```css
button:active {
    transform: scale(0.95);
}
```

### :first-child

Targets the first child element.

```css
li:first-child {
    color: red;
}
```

### :last-child

Targets the last child element.

```css
li:last-child {
    color: green;
}
```

### :nth-child()

Targets a specific child.

```css
li:nth-child(2) {
    color: blue;
}
```

## Real World Example

E-commerce websites use hover effects on product cards to improve user engagement.

## Best Practices

- Avoid excessive hover animations.
- Ensure focus states remain accessible.
- Use pseudo classes to improve user experience.

## Summary

Pseudo classes help create dynamic and interactive web interfaces.
